[3] Suspected, research, funding

2 Oct 2015 Antigua: Authorities say teacher does not have Ebola virus
http://caribbeannewsservice.com/now/authorities-say-teacher-does-not-have-ebola-virus
[Health authorities are working to reassure citizens that a teacher who recently returned from a visit to Nigeria and fell ill at a public school on Thursday (1 Oct 2015) does not have Ebola virus disease (EVD). The teacher was admitted to Mount St John's Medical Center by the Emergency Medical Service (EMS). Media reports on Friday (2 Oct 2015) said the teacher had recently traveled to Nigeria to attend the funeral of a relative.]

30 Sep 2015: Gambia to erect 6 Ebola containment centers -- official
http://en.starafrica.com/news/gambia-to-erect-six-ebola-containment-centres-official.html
[According to reports on Wednesday (30 Sep 2015), to enhance border surveillance the Gambian government has secured D 10 million (USD 256 870) in funding from the United Nation Development Program (UNDP), meant to build 6 Ebola containment centers (ETC) at 6 border points across the country. The ETCs will be used to quarantine for 21 days anyone who exhibits Ebola virus disease (EVD) symptoms. Gambia is a riverine West African country completely surrounded by Senegal except for its outlet to the sea; see map at http://www.kiteflier.co.in/map/senegal.gif. - Mod.JW]

2 Oct 2015 Italy: Genoa patient had malaria not Ebola
http://www.ansa.it/english/news/2015/10/02/genoa-patient-had-malaria-not-ebola_b02b5230-e044-4b24-bf80-f52077824cf2.html
[On Friday (2 Oct 2015), doctors confirmed a suspected Ebola virus disease (EVD) case was actually malaria after a 2nd round of blood tests were EVD-negative. The patient, an engineer from Sierra Leone who had been placed in isolation in a Genoa hospital since Wed (30 Sep 2015) after presenting with high fever, will likely be released at the weekend.]

2 Oct 2015 Liberia: Nyenswah tells world "Liberia has effectively beaten Ebola"
http://www.heritageliberia.net/heritagenews/index.php/2014-07-17-10-02-56/also-on-heritage/item/1222-nyenswah-tells-world-liberia-has-effectively-beaten-ebola
[At "The Path Towards Universal Health Coverage" meeting, deputy health minister Tolbert Nyenswah told the global community that Liberia has effectively beaten the Ebola virus twice and that the country has the capacity to deal with any resurgence.]

2 Oct 2015 Liberia: Fistula cases spiked due to Ebola outbreak
http://allafrica.com/stories/201510021046.html
[The head of Liberia Fistula Project Dr John Mulbah has disclosed that there are many cases of fistula in the country due to the deadly Ebola outbreak. Dr Mulbah blamed the alarming rate of increase of fistula cases on the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreaks because during the health crisis, several women were abandoned without access to quality maternal care. Dr Mulbah thanked the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) for the support to help eliminate fistula in Liberia.]

4 Oct 2015 New Zealand: Ebola plans "seriously flawed," denied
http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11523421
[Concerns include New Zealand's emergency plan being "light" on "disease management"; there is a low stock of protective equipment for frontline health care workers; there is a lack of adequate options for transporting patients, and there is insufficient staff training and preparation. But another report says it is prepared: http://www.newstalkzb.co.nz/news/health/nz-would-be-prepared-if-ebola-struck

Non-governmental organizations
------------------------------
30 Sep 2015 USA (TX): Kids with Ebola, bird flu or TB? Texas Children's Hospital will be ready
http://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2015/09/30/444254315/kids-with-ebola-bird-flu-or-tb-texas-childrens-hospital-will-be-ready?utm_medium=RSS&utm_campaign=healthcare
[Texas Children's has built an entirely new biocontainment wing for children. The USD 16 million project includes a separate area with 10 regular pediatric beds. The facility was funded from the hospital's capital funds and USD one million in donations. The facility is capable of treating a child with MERS (Middle East respiratory syndrome), tuberculosis, pandemic influenza, avian influenza, and other unknown pathogens. The 8 bio-containment child-treatment rooms in the facility each have an antechamber where workers will don their PPE (personal protective equipment). After treatment of the child, the worker will enter a 3rd room by a separate door where they will doff their PPE. The facility has its own biosafety laboratory and a separate medical waste room. Following every shift, workers will shower before exiting the unit.]

30 Sep 2015: Lessons from Ebola: Improving infectious disease surveillance to inform outbreak management
http://stm.sciencemag.org/content/7/307/307rv5
[journal citation: Woodhouse ME, Rambaut A, Kellam P. Lessons from Ebola: improving infectious disease surveillance to inform outbreak management. Science Translational Medicine, 30 Sep 2015: Vol. 7, Issue 307, pp. 307rv5 <DOI: 10.1126/scitranslmed.aab0191>].

Vaccines, drugs, research
-------------------------
2 Oct 2015 Russia: Testing of Russian Ebola vaccine on volunteers shows "very good" results
http://sputniknews.com/russia/20151002/1027918690/ebola-russia-vaccine-results.html#ixzz3nRbQU2Rb
[According to Russia's health minister, Veronika Skvortsova, on Fri (2 Oct 2015), Phase I clinical trials of a Russian vaccine against the Ebola virus (EBOV) showed "very good results". The vaccine was tested on around 200 healthy volunteers, and was "very well tolerated and had a very low percentage of minor side effects". Skvortsova added that Phase II trials to determine the level of vaccine's strength of antibody response were about to begin. Researchers hope to get preliminary results in November 2015, with final results on the 2nd stage due in December 2015, she said.]

1 Oct 2015 USA: NewLink Ebola vaccine research awarded USD 18 million
http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/money/business/2015/10/01/newlink-ebola-vaccine-research-awarded-18-million/73138496/
[NewLink Genetics announced on Thu 1 Oct 2015 that it has received a USD 18 million contract from BARDA (Biomedical Advanced Research and Development Authority) to support its research into an Ebola vaccine. Last week (25 Sep 2015), a NewLink subsidiary received an additional USD 8.1-million from a separate federal agency to support its vaccine research. The Defense Threat Reduction Agency (DTRA) awarded one of NewLink's subsidiaries a USD 8.1-million base contract for work on the Ebola vaccine rVSV-ZEBOV, with the possibility of an additional USD 5.2 million in the future.]

2 Oct 2015 USA: FDA fast tracks Ebola drug
http://www.dailyrxnews.com/zmapp-ebola-drug-gets-fast-track-status-us-food-and-drug-administration
[The US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has granted "fast track" approval for Mapp Biopharmaceutical's ZMapp, an experimental drug used to treat the 1st American to be infected with Ebola. ZMapp's previous status was "orphan drug, which allowed financial incentives for ZMapp's development.]

[compiled by: Celeste Whitlow <whitlow.celeste@gmail.com>]

